<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-squares-and-rectangles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Squares and Rectangles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_cl9rmil1">
            <p xml:id="auto_mh77369f">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_05r9r303">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ioe8z40u">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yjquv1ng">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ukvrj76l">
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zzvjeatd">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_sgig1hvl">
                        Determine the area of quadrilaterals in different situations. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vasglu3h" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gogmv8mf">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uadum704" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1om8bcvw">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j38u559c" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_hx7286sq"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vurvvmfw">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qcydyu48">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define area as the amount of surface covered by a two-dimensional shape, measured in square units. Identify rectangles and squares as quadrilaterals with right angles and parallel sides. State the area formulas: Area of rectangle <m>= \text{length} \times \text{width}</m> and Area of square <m>= \text{side}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_yop58lfw">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2ioe66d6">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of rectangles and squares using the formulas. Find missing dimensions (length, width, or side) given the area. Verify area by counting unit squares on grid paper.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_p7tzx0zn">
                        <p xml:id="auto_j6tnq0pr">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving areas of squares and rectangles (fields, gardens, classrooms). Compare areas of different shapes. Apply area concepts to practical design and tiling problems.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_ob4zuuid">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-squares-and-rectangles.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_76afvxu9">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-squares-and-rectangles.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <p xml:id="auto_mrep9518">
        The <term>area</term> of a two-dimensional shape is the amount of surface it covers, 
        measured in square units (e.g., cm², m²). A quadrilateral with all right angles 
        and opposite sides parallel is called a <term>rectangle</term>. When all four sides 
        are equal, then it becomes a <term>square</term>.
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Discovering Area Through Counting</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qtjh6gpy">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_c06thp0f">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gu3ds5xq">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_k1zl7at3">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_iloe39vp">
                    Groups of 2–3 students
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8n7342by">
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3xvi5unk">
                    Distribute grid/graph paper and rulers to each group. Ensure students can see the rectangle (<m>6 \times 4</m>) and square (<m>5 \times 5</m>) diagrams.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_d5e6vp4x">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_hq5wzbqg">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_3pwyrs4j">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ge6wpdvm">
                                Circulate among groups to observe counting strategies.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4op4l75l">
                            <p xml:id="auto_stfo0wfg">
                                Ask probing questions: <q>How many rows do you see?</q>, <q>How many squares in each row?</q>, <q>Can multiplication help you count faster?</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2r3x3vr8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_y783wfzk">
                                Guide students to see that multiplication is faster than counting individual squares.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ogtv26jj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_v174r4s4">
                                Encourage students to articulate the pattern they observe between side lengths and area.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_x9yr8af1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_e27pb682">
                                Use student discoveries as a bridge to the formal area formulas.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_b5znm3i3">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_n2ipxfgd">
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ac98b0by">
                <term>Materials:</term> Grid/graph paper and a ruler
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ri1kxd84">
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_k3uragnv">
                Consider the rectangle below:
            </p>

            <image width="45%">
                <latex-image label="rectangle-area-visual">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray!40,very thin] (0,0) grid (6,4);
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (6,4);
                        \node[below] at (3,0) {$6$ units};
                        \node[left] at (0,2) {$4$ units};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_f0qxqoln">Count the number of unit squares inside the rectangle.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3f7js8cv">Verify your answer using multiplication.</li>
            </ol>

            <p xml:id="auto_xih256ad">
                Now consider the square below:
            </p>

            <image width="40%">
                <latex-image label="square-area-visual">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
                        \draw[step=1cm,gray!40,very thin] (0,0) grid (5,5);
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (5,5);
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$5$ units};
                        \node[left] at (0,2.5) {$5$ units};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_ir38qxce">Count the number of unit squares inside the square.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_06os0to7">Verify your answer using multiplication.</li>
            </ol>

            <p xml:id="auto_vk68aj17">
                What relationship do you observe between the side lengths and the number of square units?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_9yucvztk">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_n8a7xhi7">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_606qolpz">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4llii7ni">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_bt1fhfef">
                    To formalise the area formulas for rectangles and squares.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_dvbyvn8s">
                Address common misconceptions revealed during the anchor activity:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a2zuypnc">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_hlmukpt6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_b4wfy7jx">
                            If students confuse perimeter with area, emphasise that area measures <q>inside</q> while perimeter measures <q>around</q>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_7bszxdk0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_93klvprs">
                            Use visual representations with grid paper to show how multiplication counts all squares.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_i6qzt601">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5jey3h9i">
                            Clarify the difference between linear units (cm, m) and square units (cm², m²).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2n4djbax">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qjzzwtu0">
                            Demonstrate that a square is a special type of rectangle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_dl7b5ld8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fo237ggp">
                            Connect to real-world contexts: floor tiles, garden plots, classroom size.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight xml:id="auto_uhkg9cw0">
        <p xml:id="auto_wipbx4iw">
            The area of a rectangle is found by multiplying its length and width:
            <me>
                \textbf{Area of rectangle} = \text{length} \times \text{width}
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zcbg4e1l">
            A square is a special rectangle where all sides are equal, so:
            <me>
                \textbf{Area of square} = \text{side} \times \text{side} = \text{side}^2
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_luxfzoz1">
            In both cases, the area represents the number of square units that fit inside the shape.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_equjsxeg">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_5pfqdpzq">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_glbh9cj9">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_iwyrxg02">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_uj8t3jcf">
                    Students apply the area formulas through worked examples and independent practice.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_yf9ne849">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_bxon3slp">
                    Work through the first two examples on the board, modelling the solution process. Then direct students to attempt the remaining examples independently. Circulate to support struggling learners. After independent work, select students to present their solutions.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_nk7nn8ge">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0hs3g0g3">
                Find the area of the following:
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_mokpgl37">A square with side <m>9 \, cm</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1x2bfkst">A rectangle with length <m>12 \, m</m> and width <m>7 \, m</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_9u4hrdi6">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dqieo28s">
                        Area of square = <me>9 \times 9 = 81 \, \text{cm}^2</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6n3tebmb">
                    <p xml:id="auto_i7x3dqjs">
                        Area of rectangle = <me>12 \times 7 = 84 \, \text{m}^2</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_m1rhscst">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_uhwzuzl8">
                A rectangular field has length <m>120 \;m</m> and width <m>75 \;m</m>. Find the area in <m>m^2</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_u3inur4h">
                Area of rectangle <m>=</m> length <m>\times</m> width
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_d4mff0rf">
                Area <m>= 120 \times 75</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bamhs3na">
                The field covers <m> 9,000 \;m^2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_ajpxdfvt">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_rbgcyihx">
                The area of a square is <m>196\; m^2</m>. Find the length of its side.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_twxdp6mt">
                Area of square <m>= \text{side}^2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vh0wykuh">
                <m>196 = \text{side}^2 </m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_or0eloaa">
                <m>\text{side} =  \sqrt{196} = 14 \;m</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5sb4q7u8">
                The side length is <m>14 \;m</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_8jc87fwi">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_06llxvlo">
                The area of a rectangle is <m>150 \;cm^2</m> and its width is <m>10 \;cm</m>. Find the length?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_rmzs8oe2">
                Area of rectangle <m>=</m> length <m>\times</m> width
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pe6yvln2">
               <m>150 = \text{length} \times 10</m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_i29zaayq">
                length <m>= 150 \div 10 = 15 \;cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mefnq7nu">
                The length is <m>15 \;cm</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_1o8zve47">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_lf6by3ji">
                <term>Students work independently</term>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8esr19a5">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_7tb4c5ql">
                        <p xml:id="auto_epmk9ify">
                           Find the area of a square with side <m>8 \;cm</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_f2d1tcsv">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0qociyo0">
                            Find the area of a rectangle with length <m>15 \;m</m> and width <m>9 \;m</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_7rxr0je0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2mrowxk4">
                            A square garden has area <m>144 \;m^2</m>. Find the length of one side
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_k30xlan2">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ylg8p9mk">
                            A rectangle has area <m>200 \;cm^2</m> and width <m>8 \;cm</m>. Find the length
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_j98pj7dw">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_hgkprk40">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_0ev3u2ds">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_3e6ezyey">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_st0su15u">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ld7zo158">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_lm26ksob">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_mlc22w0q">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_x2kf1iuq">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify common misconceptions.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="auto_h4zkm29i">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_n2zc9j2y">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0blyub6l">
                    Find the area of a square with side <m>15 \, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_iuutano3">
                    <m>225 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_zwj0vvk5">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_q6i82ajz">
                    Find the area of a rectangle with length <m>8 \, \text{m}</m> and width <m>5 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_rbvnlo8g">
                    <m>40 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_9f4kmok3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_84yadsbw">
                    A rectangular field has length <m>120 \, m</m> and width <m>75 \, m</m>. Find the area in <m>m^2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_1wx1pb5a">
                    <m>9000 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_7v6fwzll">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_936v0t0v">
                    The area of a square is <m>196 \, m^2</m>. Find the length of its side.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_x01ww26m">
                    <m>14 \, m</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_1pzo7da6">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mwzi6swq">
                    The area of a rectangle is <m>150 \, cm^2</m> and its width is <m>10 \, cm</m>. Find the length.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_nh2q3bbj">
                    <m>15 \, cm</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_u908pfy2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_cq0zgyan">
                    Which has a greater area:
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_xgzmab4i">a square with side <m>14 \, cm</m>, or</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_qh3hsv31">a rectangle with length <m>18 \, cm</m> and width <m>10 \, cm</m>?</li>
                        </ul>
                        Show your working.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_fw6m0gcs">
                    Area of square = <m>14 \times 14 = 196 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                    Area of rectangle = <m>18 \times 10 = 180 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                    Therefore, the square has a greater area.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_m1awk33k">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_v7insfpa">
                    Find the area of a rectangle with length <m>(2x + 3) \text{cm}</m> and width <m>(x - 1) \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_ic9wsmyi">
                    <m>(2x + 3)(x - 1) = 2x^2 + x - 3 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_w1i15f2n">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_3dk974fu">
                    A square garden has area <m>256 \, m^2</m>. One side is increased by <m>2 \, m</m>. Find the new area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_0pv0cz8a">
                    <m>324 \, m^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_2jopwvvh">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_mwcvk40e">
                    A classroom floor measures <m>9 \, m</m> by <m>7 \, m</m>. If each floor tile covers <m>1 \, m^2</m>, how many tiles are required?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_22ooi4qm">
                    <m>63 \, \text{tiles}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_wa2bwmn5">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_i59ohd0c">
                    A rectangular wall is <m>12 \, m</m> long and <m>3 \, m</m> high. If one litre of paint covers <m>6 \, m^2</m>, how many litres of paint are needed?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_crw4gemg">
                    <m>6 \, \text{litres}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_twwzeaya">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_7uo56l41">
                    A farmer wants to fence a rectangular plot measuring <m>50 \, m</m> by <m>30 \, m</m>.
                        Calculate:
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1h8t1q5i">(i) the area of the plot,</li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_naa72dy9">(ii) the perimeter of the plot.</li>
                        </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_qj708j2j">
                    (i) Area = <m>1500 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                    (ii) Perimeter = <m>160 \, \text{m}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_f5ckt8de">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_u80jhezk">
                    A square piece of land has side <m>x \, m</m>. Write an expression for its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_3n4j0vjt">
                    <m>x^2 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_k79nr1mt">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_7igr9n55">
                    A rectangle has length <m>(x + 4)</m> metres and width <m>6</m> metres. Form an algebraic expression for its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_0evss85i">
                    <m>6(x + 4) = 6x + 24 \,\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_vkhqxvi8">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_233nfgn4">
                    A rectangular field has length <m>(2x - 1)</m> metres and width <m>(x + 3)</m> metres. Form an expression for its area and simplify.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_25igpmfu">
                    <m>(2x - 1)(x + 3) = 2x^2 + 5x - 3 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_8g30vdx3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_zcpwcy7q">
                    A square has side <m>(x + 3)</m> cm. Form and simplify an expression for its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_gipvef7w">
                    <m>(x + 3)^2 = x^2 + 6x + 9 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_ktjrs9nh">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ccq4ddcr">
                    The length of a rectangle is twice its width. If the width is <m>x</m> metres, form an expression for its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_qqk71mw1">
                    <m>2x \times x = 2x^2 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_jspdkpoy">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_tppm4mpk">
                    A rectangular playground is <m>40 \, m</m> long and <m>25 \, m</m> wide. A path of width <m>2 \, m</m> is built all around the outside. Find the area covered by the path.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_eyeyl56d">
                    Area of playground = <m>40 \times 25 = 1000 \,\text{m}^2</m>
                    Area of playground + path = <m>(40 + 4)(25 + 4) = 44 \times 29 = 1276 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                    Area of path = <m>1276 - 1000 = 276 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_ksscb52x">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_eucrsjz2">
                    A square metal sheet has side <m>20 \, cm</m>. A smaller square of side <m>8 \, cm</m> is cut from one corner. Find the remaining area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_raz10oik">
                    <m>336 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_db3av9lh">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_v5sd942o">
                A rectangular garden is <m>30 \, m</m> long and <m>18 \, m</m> wide. A square pond of side <m>6 \, m</m> is built inside the garden. Find the remaining area of the garden.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_9xqzokzs">
                    Area of garden = <m>30 \times 18 = 540 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                    Area of pond = <m>6 \times 6 = 36 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                    Remaining area = <m>540 - 36 = 504 \, \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_konx3nt3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qqc0q8mu">
                    A square tile has an area of <m>64 \, \text{cm}^2</m>. Find the length of one side of the tile.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_hsqt3qui">
                    <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_s9w02rza">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_sju7y4cp">
                    The length of a rectangle exceeds its width by <m>4 \, \text{m}</m>. If the area is <m>105 \, \text{m}^2</m>, find the dimensions of the rectangle and its perimeter.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_quthhd2q">
                    Let the width be <m>x\,\text{m}</m>, so the length is <m>x+4\,\text{m}</m>.
                    Area equation: <me>x(x+4)=105</me> gives
                    <me>x^2+4x-105=0.</me>
                    Factorising, <me>(x+15)(x-7)=0</me>, so the positive solution is <m>x=7\,\text{m}</m>.
                    Thus the length is <m>11\,\text{m}</m>.
                    Dimensions: <m>7\,\text{m}</m> by <m>11\,\text{m}</m>.
                    Perimeter: <me>2(7+11)=36\,\text{m}</me>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_agk6pvjm">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide grid paper with shapes already drawn for counting practice. Use manipulatives (square tiles) to physically build rectangles and squares. Create a reference card with formulas and examples. Allow use of calculators. Start with smaller numbers before progressing to larger dimensions. Pair with stronger students for peer support.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Encourage students to draw their own diagrams from word problems. Provide mixed practice with both direct calculation and finding missing dimensions.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Introduce algebraic expressions for dimensions (e.g., length <m>= 2x</m>, width <m>= x</m>). Challenge with composite shapes (L-shapes made from rectangles). Explore how area changes when dimensions are doubled or tripled. Solve optimisation problems (maximum area for given perimeter). Connect to square roots for working backwards from area.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity: Classroom Floor Planning</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_lbv4ghyq">
                Students measure the classroom floor dimensions, calculate the total floor area in square metres, and design a new classroom layout with different zones (reading area, group work area, teacher area). They calculate the area of each zone ensuring all zones fit within the total floor area. If floor tiles are <m>1 \, \text{m}^2</m> each, they calculate how many tiles are needed. Students present their designs with calculations to the class.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

